Here is a clear, deep, interview-ready explanation of Application Load Balancer (ALB) and Network Load Balancer (NLB) with use cases, features, diagrams, and differences.

âœ… Application Load Balancer (ALB)

Layer: L7 (Application Layer â€“ HTTP/HTTPS/WebSocket)

The Application Load Balancer is used for web applications, microservices, and modern architectures.
It understands HTTP and HTTPS protocols, so it can inspect the request content and make intelligent routing decisions.

ğŸ”¹ Key Features of ALB
1ï¸âƒ£ Path-based Routing

Route traffic based on URL paths:

/login â†’ Auth Service

/products â†’ Product Service

/cart â†’ Cart Service

2ï¸âƒ£ Host-based Routing

Route based on domains:

api.example.com â†’ API servers

admin.example.com â†’ Admin application

3ï¸âƒ£ Microservices Support

Each microservice runs on separate EC2/containers but ALB handles routing.

4ï¸âƒ£ HTTPS/SSL Termination

ALB can decrypt HTTPS traffic using ACM certificates.

5ï¸âƒ£ WebSockets Support
6ï¸âƒ£ Sticky Sessions (Session Affinity)

ALB can send a user to the same instance during the session.

7ï¸âƒ£ Health Checks

Checks /health path of web apps.

ğŸ”¥ When to Use ALB

Web applications (HTTP/HTTPS)

Microservices architecture

Path-based or host-based routing

When you want to offload SSL/TLS certificates

Dynamic routing based on URL or headers

Integration with ECS/EKS services

