âœ… Network Load Balancer (NLB)

Layer: L4 (Transport Layer â€“ TCP/UDP/TLS)

The Network Load Balancer is designed for high-performance, ultra-low latency, and millions of requests per second.

It does not understand HTTP.
It only forwards traffic based on IP and port.

ğŸ”¹ Key Features of NLB
1ï¸âƒ£ Handles Millions of Requests/Second

Extremely high throughput.

2ï¸âƒ£ Ultra-Low Latency

Latency is usually under 1 millisecond.

3ï¸âƒ£ TCP/UDP Protocol Support

Used for real-time applications.

4ï¸âƒ£ Static IP Support

You can assign:

Fixed static IP

Elastic IPs

One static IP per AZ

Great for on-premise integrations.

5ï¸âƒ£ TLS Pass-through

TLS certificates stay on backend servers.

6ï¸âƒ£ Preserves Client Source IP

Backend servers can see real client IP.

7ï¸âƒ£ Very High Performance Health Checks
ğŸ”¥ When to Use NLB

Highly scalable applications

Real-time streaming

Gaming servers

Database traffic

Financial transaction systems

Applications needing static IP or EIP

Low latency TCP/UDP traffic

ğŸ“˜ Simple NLB Example
User â†’ NLB â†’ EC2-1 (TCP app)
            â†’ EC2-2 (Database proxy)
            â†’ EC2-3 (Real-time system)

ğŸ†š ALB vs NLB â€“ Quick Comparison
Feature	ALB	NLB
Layer	Layer 7	Layer 4
Protocol	HTTP/HTTPS/WSS	TCP/UDP/TLS
Routing	Path/Host-based	IP+Port
Performance	Good	Highest (millions of req/sec)
Latency	Milliseconds	Sub-millisecond
Static IP	No	Yes
SSL Termination	Yes	No (passes through)
Use case	Web apps, microservices	Real-time, high performance
Client IP Visibility	Via X-Forwarded-For header	Native
